  "response_text": "The temporal evolution of the aggregate livestock population begins at a mean value of 90.0000 at timestep 0. The system enters a phase of rapid adjustment characterized by a sustained decline, reaching a local and global minimum of 41.0089 at index 37. This initial descent is supported by significant negative trends in the early rolling windows, such as the first decade which shows a steep slope. A structural break occurs around timestep 20, marking a shift in the rate of decline before the series bottoms out. Following the minimum at index 37, the downward pressure abates, and the trend inverts. Subsequent rolling analyses (e.g., index 44 to 54) confirm a shift to a significant positive trend (tau=1.000). By the conclusion of the simulation at timestep 100, the population has recovered slightly to 47.5472. This dynamic suggests an initial structural realignment where agents reduce herd sizes, likely in response to carrying capacity constraints, before the system stabilizes at a new, lower equilibrium level."
}

